04881nam a22006615i 9780822390329DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20082007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223903297 a10.1515/97808223903292doi  a(DE-B1597)553350  a(OCoLC)1148139261  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHX84.J66bB69 2008 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a941.085/092aB2221 aDavies, Carole Boyce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLeft of Karl Marx :bThe Political Life of Black Communist Claudia Jones /cCarole Boyce Davies. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (340 p.) :b31 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tChronology -- tIntroduction. Recovering the Radical Black Female Subject -- t1. Women's Rights/Workers' Rights/Anti-Imperialism -- t2. From ''Half the World'' to the Whole World -- t3. Prison Blues -- t4. Deportation: The Other Politics of Diaspora -- t5. Carnival and Diaspora -- t6. Piece Work/Peace Work -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Left of Karl Marx, Carole Boyce Davies assesses the activism, writing, and legacy of Claudia Jones (1915-1964), a pioneering Afro-Caribbean radical intellectual, dedicated communist, and feminist. Jones is buried in London's Highgate Cemetery, to the left of Karl Marx-a location that Boyce Davies finds fitting given how Jones expanded Marxism-Leninism to incorporate gender and race in her political critique and activism.Claudia Cumberbatch Jones was born in Trinidad. In 1924, she moved to New York, where she lived for the next thirty years. She was active in the Communist Party from her early twenties onward. A talented writer and speaker, she traveled throughout the United States lecturing and organizing. In the early 1950s, she wrote a well-known column, "Half the World," for the Daily Worker. As the U.S. government intensified its efforts to prosecute communists, Jones was arrested several times. She served nearly a year in a U.S. prison before being deported and given asylum by Great Britain in 1955. There she founded The West Indian Gazette and Afro-Asian Caribbean News and the Caribbean Carnival, an annual London festival that continues today as the Notting Hill Carnival. Boyce Davies examines Jones's thought and journalism, her political and community organizing, and poetry that the activist wrote while she was imprisoned. Looking at the contents of the FBI file on Jones, Boyce Davies contrasts Jones's own narration of her life with the federal government's. Left of Karl Marx establishes Jones as a significant figure within Caribbean intellectual traditions, black U.S. feminism, and the history of communism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aFeministszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aFeministszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWest IndianszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWest IndianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen and communismzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen and communismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen communistszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWomen communistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen journalistszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWomen journalistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen's rightszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen's rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390329zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.c